SIMPLE: seventh
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Seventh
<hw>Sev"enth</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Seven</er>:
cf. AS. <ets>seofo⟦edh⟧a</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Next in order
after the sixth;; coming after six others.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On the <qex>seventh</qex> day, God ended his work which he had
made; and he rested on the <qex>seventh</qex> day from all his work
which he had made.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. ii. 2.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Constituting or being one of seven equal parts into
which anything is divided; <as>as, the <ex>seventh</ex>
part</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Seventh day</b></col>, <cd>the seventh day of the week;
Saturday.</cd> -- <col><b>Seventh-day Baptists</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Baptist</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seventh</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Seventh
<hw>Sev"enth</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One next in order
after the sixth; one coming after six others.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The quotient of a unit divided by seven; one of
seven equal parts into which anything is divided.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>An interval embracing
seven diatonic degrees of the scale.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A chord
which includes the interval of a seventh whether major, minor, or
diminished.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seven-thirties</ent>⟦br⟧
